		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.17]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Debalic&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>There are a few quick things to consider with pets and weapons.<br /><br />For the double-damage benefit, get 2-handed weapons. Rusty scythes, two-handed swords, halberds, etc. Since the lower-level pets (that will benefit from the damage) can't dual wield, one weapon is all you need. <br /><br />Later on (between 20-30) your pet will start to dual-wield, albeit poorly. You will need to give the pet two weapons to force dual-wielding at first - rusty daggers are perfectly suitable for this. After 29 or so, the pet will DW on its own.<br /><br />Proccing weapons are great for pets. You can even load up on Velium weaps and, once level appropriate, give to the pet for procs (but you will lose that 5pp weapon). </p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />Dear President Bush,<br /><br />Please don't get us all killed.<br /><br />Yours (for another four years),<br />The American People</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from New York (no, not the city)</td></tr></table>
